stem-level testing to account for OS scheduling and actual timing behavior. Since the core concern is whether the handler responds immediately after queueing rather than blocking, integration testing covers it—I can use a real queue with concurrent requests and verify response times don't degrade. Confidence shifts to 0.85 for integration.\n\nFor deduplication, the minimum level depends on how the dedup mechanism works. If it's a simple in-memory store, unit testing might suffice. But if it involves a database or distributed cache, integration testing becomes necessary to verify the dedup logic actually prevents duplicate events from being queued.\n\nQueue full error handling is straightforward at the unit level—I can mock the queue to throw an error and verify the handler returns a 503 with Retry-After. Queue capacity enforcement, though, requires a real queue with actual capacity limits to test whether the system properly rejects writes when full.\n\nFor the signature validation behavior, I need to reconsider the test approach. The requirement is that an invalid signature results in a 401 response and the body isn't forwarded to the queue. At unit level, I can mock the queue and verify both the response code and that the queue wasn't called when signature validation fails.\n\nThe ordering behavior—ensuring the queue write completes before sending the HTTP 200—requires checking that the queue operation is awaited. In an async handler, if the code properly awaits the queue write before calling `res.status(200).send()`, this can be tested at unit level by mocking the queue with a delayed response and verifying the response isn't sent until after the mock resolves. return a promise that doesn't resolve immediately, and then verify the response isn't sent until that promise settles. This approach is fragile though since it requires precise control over async timing.\n\nAn integration test would be more reliable—make an actual request to the handler with a mocked queue that tracks timing, then confirm the queue operation completes before the HTTP response. Unit tests can work here with good mocks, but they're trickier to get right.\n\nI'm leaning toward integration testing for this scenario (0.6 confidence on integration, 0.4 on unit).\n\nActually, the unit test approach could work if I set up the mocks correctly:\n\n```javascript\ntest('queue write happens before response', async () => {\n  const queue = {\n    write: jest.fn().mockResolvedValue(undefined)\n  };\n  \n  const mockRes = {\n    status: jest.fn().mockReturnThis(),\n    json: jest.fn()\n  };\n  \n  await handleWebhook({body: ...}, mockRes);\n  \n  expect(queue.write).toHaveBeenCalled();\n  expect(mockRes.json).toHaveBeenCalled();\n});\n```\n\nThe real challenge is verifying the order of operations. Jest has call order tracking but it's not elegant. Integration testing handles this more naturally—spin up a real HTTP request, instrument the queue with timing markers, and confirm the write finishes before the response goes out. That's probably the right level for catching this specific failure mode (0.7 confidence on integration).\n\nThe core issue is that mocking the queue to resolve immediately masks whether the handler actually awaits it. If the code does `queue.write(event)` without awaiting, the test still passes because both operations complete quickly. I need to think about what would actually catch that bug.\n\nUsing a call order tracker with controlled promise resolution works at the unit level:\n\n```javascript\nlet queueResolve;\nconst queue = {\n  write: jest.fn(() => new Promise(resolve => { queueResolve = resolve; }))\n};\n\nconst callOrder = [];\nconst mockRes = {\n  json: jest.fn(() => { callOrder.push('res.json'); })\n};\n\nawait handleWebhook({body: ...}, mockRes);\nqueueResolve();\n\nexpect(callOrder).toEqual(['queue.write']);\n```\n\nThis forces the queue promise to stay pending until I explicitly resolve it, which reveals whether res.json gets called prematurely.\n\nThe real issue emerges when the handler doesn't await the queue write—the HTTP response sends immediately while the queue operation is still in flight. Catching this requires verifying that res.json fires before the queue promise resolves, which a unit test can validate by controlling promise timing. The queue write shouldn't resolve yet, so you can verify the promise ordering at the unit level. This approach is sufficient because you're mocking the queue to control when it resolves, allowing you to assert that the response is sent before the queue operation completes.\n\nFor the three behaviors being tested:\n\n**Signature validation rejection** requires unit-level testing with mocked dependencies to verify the 401 response on invalid signatures. **Queue write ordering** can be tested at unit level by mocking the queue with a controllable promise, confirming the response fires before the queue resolves. **Response without waiting for downstream operations** needs integration testing to verify the handler actually returns immediately without awaiting the queue write, since this involves the actual async behavior of the handler itself.\n\nThe remaining behaviors follow similar patterns: response time under load and queue capacity enforcement require integration or system-level testing with realistic queue behavior, while queue full error handling can be unit tested with a mocked queue that throws an error. Deduplication typically requires persistent storage, pushing it toward integration testing.\n\nChecking consistency across all behaviors: each test level aligns with the infrastructure needed to catch the real failure mode. Unit tests handle signature validation and promise ordering with mocked queues, while integration tests verify non-blocking behavior, performance under load, deduplication logic, and capacity enforcement with real queue instances and downstream processors.\n\nNow I need to write out the test descriptions. But first, let me reconsider behaviors 3 and 4 together since they're related. Behavior 3 is about not blocking on downstream work—the handler should return immediately. Behavior 4 is about meeting a 3-second response time even when earlier events are processing slowly. The distinction matters: behavior 3 tests that we don't wait at all, while behavior 4 tests that we stay within a time budget under concurrent load. Both require a slow downstream processor to expose the failure, but behavior 3 just needs to verify immediate response while behavior 4 needs actual timing measurements.\n\nFor behavior 3, I could test at the unit level if I use a real queue but mock the downstream consumer. The handler code just enqueues and responds, so I'd verify the response comes back right after the queue write completes, independent of any downstream processing. The key is ensuring the handler truly doesn't block on downstream work—it just puts the event in the queue and returns.\n\nHowever, this is really an architectural concern that's better validated at integration level. With a real queue and an intentionally slow downstream processor, I can confirm the handler actually responds quickly without waiting. A mocked queue might hide whether the handler is inadvertently blocking, so integration testing gives me more confidence here. test, you could mock the queue and verify it's called. The handler should return immediately after enqueueing, without waiting for actual processing. A real integration test would be more valuable though—spinning up a slow downstream processor and confirming the response comes back quickly, which better captures the actual failure mode where downstream processing blocks the handler.\n\nLet me look at behavior 4 again.\n\nBehavior 4 is about response latency under concurrent load. The key failure mode is when response time exceeds 3 seconds, which happens when a slow downstream processor backs up earlier requests. Testing this properly requires a real queue, a slow (or mocked) downstream processor, and multiple concurrent requests with timing measurements to verify each response stays under the threshold. This is solidly an integration concern since you need those real components interacting, though system-level testing could apply if OS-level timing matters. I'm fairly confident integration testing is the right level here.\n\nNow reconsidering behavior 5.\n\nDeduplication is the core requirement—the handler must prevent the same event ID from being queued twice. The failure mode is straightforward: duplicate event IDs end up in the queue. Testing involves sending the same event ID twice and confirming it only appears once. The tricky part is how the handler tracks what it's already seen. An in-memory set is fast but doesn't survive restarts, while a database or cache provides durability. For a webhook handler that needs to be resilient, you'd typically use persistent storage. At the unit level, you could mock the deduplication mechanism, but you'd need to verify the actual persistence layer works correctly at integration level. but Unit tests work if deduplication stays in-memory. For production systems though, I'd expect persistent deduplication using a database or cache layer, which requires Integration testing to verify the actual behavior across restarts.\n\nConfidence leans toward Integration at 0.75, with Unit at 0.25 since the in-memory approach is simpler but less realistic for real webhooks.\n\nNow I can finalize the response. I should make sure each test description clearly states what infrastructure it needs and what failure it would catch.\n\nFor \"Signature validation rejected with 401\": Unit test with mocked queue—verify that an invalid signature returns 401 and doesn't trigger a queue write.\n\nFor \"Queue write before response\": Unit test with a mock queue that delays resolution—verify the response doesn't send until the queue write completes.\n\nFor \"Response without waiting for downstream\": Integration test with a real queue and slow downstream processor—verify the response returns immediately after queuing, not after downstream processing finishes.\n\nFor \"Duplicate event handling\":\n- Test: \"Integration test with persistent deduplication store (database/cache): send duplicate event IDs and verify only one is written to the queue\"\n\nFor \"Queue full error handling\": Unit test with a mock queue throwing a 'full' error—verify the handler returns 503 with a Retry-After header.\n\nFor \"Queue capacity enforcement\": Integration test with a real queue—fill it to capacity and verify the next write is rejected.\n\nNow I need to check plan_consistent for each behavior—whether the test_description actually requires the minimum_level or if it would pass at a lower level. Behavior 1 (Unit, signature validation) would pass at Unit level since it's a local function. Behavior 2 (Unit, queue write ordering) can be tested with mocks to verify promise sequencing. Behavior 3 (Integration, downstream response timing) requires a real queue to confirm the response timing behavior.\n\nBehavior 4 (Integration, concurrent requests under load) needs wall-clock measurements that unit tests can't reliably provide. Behavior 5 (Integration, deduplication) requires a persistent store to verify the deduplication logic works end-to-end. Behavior 6 (Unit, error handling) can be tested with a mock queue throwing an error. Behavior 7 (Integration, capacity limits) needs a real queue to fill and test rejection behavior. - a real queue is necessary to validate capacity constraints. At the Integration level, this would pass. plan_consistent: true\n\nEverything checks out. Now I'll structure the output.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":12483,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":12483},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"}